  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Sextic polynomial oscillator is probably the best known quantum system which is partially exactly alias quasi-exactly solvable (QES), i.e., which possesses closed-form, elementary-function bound states <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> at certain couplings and energies. In contrast, the apparently simpler and phenomenologically more important quartic polynomial oscillator is not QES. A resolution of the paradox is proposed: The one-dimensional Schrödinger equation is shown QES after the analyticity-violating symmetrization <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>V</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi><msup><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mi>x</mi><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">|</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math> of the quartic polynomial potential.</subfield>
